  "prompt": "How do you choose an unresponsive yoyo?",
  "response": "Choosing an unresponsive yoyo involves considering several factors, including:\n\n1. **Bearing Type**: An unresponsive yoyo typically has a specialized ball bearing that allows the yoyo to spin freely and return only when a bind is performed. Common bearings for unresponsive yoyos include C-size bearings.\n\n2. **Response System**: Unresponsive yoyos use a response system designed to provide minimal friction, enabling advanced tricks. Silicone pads, flush mounts, or specialized response systems like YYF CBC pads or YoyoRecreation IRPads are popular choices.\n\n3. **Weight Distribution**: To choose an unresponsive yoyo, consider a design with a weight distribution that offers stability and long spin times. Look for yoyos with rim weight to maximize performance.\n\n4. **Material and Build Quality**: Unresponsive yoyos are often made of durable materials like aluminum, bi-metal, or high-quality plastics. An anodized aluminum yoyo is a common choice for durability and precision.\n\n5. **Skill Level**: Ensure you're selecting a yoyo designed for unresponsive play and suitable for your skill level. Beginners might prefer a yoyo with a wider string gap to make binds easier, while advanced players can handle more aggressive designs.\n\n6. **Shape and Size**: Unresponsive yoyos come in various shapes (e.g., butterfly, v-shape) and sizes. The shape and size affect stability, string hits, and comfort, so choose one that feels right for you.\n\n7. **Brand and Model Reviews**: Research brands that are known for producing high-quality unresponsive yoyos, like YoYoFactory, Duncan, One Drop, and YoyoRecreation. Read reviews and see feedback from other users in the yoyo community.\n\nBy considering these factors, you'll be able to select an unresponsive yoyo that matches your preferences and enhances your performance in yoyo tricks.",
